I used a reset synchronizer, but STA still fails with a Removal time violation on my state machine. The timing report notes huge skew on the reset net. Why?
module buggy_reset(input clk, input raw_rst, output [1:0] state);
  // Sync logic
  reg r1, r2; 
  always @(posedge clk) {r2, r1} <= {r1, raw_rst};

  // FSM Logic
  fsm_core u_core (.clk(clk), .rst(r2), .state(state));
endmodule

output:
### Functional Explanation
This code correctly implements a synchronization chain (`r1`, `r2`) to bring `raw_rst` into the `clk` domain, before piping it to an FSM logic core as a synchronous reset.

### Potential Issues
1. **Fabric Routing Skew (High Fan-out)**: The final register in the synchronizer chain (`r2`) is a standard slice flip-flop driving `u_core`. If `u_core` contains hundreds of flip-flops, the `rst` net becomes an exponentially high fan-out signal. Because `r2` is not buffered onto the global clock tree, it must route through slow, high-resistance local fabric. The `rst` signal will arrive at some flip-flops near the source instantly, and others very late. This massive routing delay and skew means the reset signal violates the `Removal time` of the flip-flops located furthest down the routing chain.

### Recommended Fix
Drive the synchronized reset net onto a global buffer (BUFG) so it utilizes the same ultra-low skew distribution network as the clock itself.
```verilog
module fixed_reset(input clk, input raw_rst, output [1:0] state);
  reg r1, r2;
  wire rst_global;

  (* ASYNC_REG = "TRUE" *) 
  always @(posedge clk) {r2, r1} <= {r1, raw_rst};

  // Force the high fan-out reset net onto the global clock routing tree
  BUFG clk_bufg_inst (.I(r2), .O(rst_global));

  fsm_core u_core (.clk(clk), .rst(rst_global), .state(state));
endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
In Vivado, tools typically replicate logic (Max Fanout Replication) automatically. However, for synchronous localized resets, replication doesn't solve high skew. Explicitly instantiating a `BUFG` reduces reset skew from nanoseconds down to picoseconds, instantly solving Setup/Recovery and Hold/Removal timing violations.

### Functional Explanation
IEEE-754 Single-Precision Floating Point consists of 1 Sign bit, 8 Exponent bits (biased by +127), and 23 Mantissa bits. To constrain the exponent to a physical value greater than `+10`, the raw exponent field must be greater than `127 + 10 = 137`.

### Potential Issues
None. This requires complex testbench UVM/OVM class topology generating raw hexadecimal representing floating point boundaries.

### Recommended Fix
```systemverilog
class float_generator;
  rand bit sign;
  rand bit [7:0] exp;
  rand bit [22:0] mantissa;

  bit [31:0] float_word;

  // To maintain exponent > +10, raw bias field must be > 137.
  // Max exponent is 254 (255 is reserved for NaN/Infinity).
  constraint c_exp_range {
    exp > 137;
    exp < 255;
  }

  // Optional: Prevent denormals or strictly zero mantissa
  constraint c_mantissa_valid {
    mantissa != 23'd0;
  }

  function void post_randomize();
    // Assemble the 32-bit floating point payload
    float_word = {sign, exp, mantissa};
    $display("Gen Float: 0x%08X (Exp Bias=%0d)", float_word, exp);
  endfunction
endclass
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
Hardware floating-point arithmetic (FPU) cores are exceptionally pipeline intensive. Testbench classes like this are critical because providing randomly distributed integers to an FPU will aggressively trigger denormal/NaN corner cases or underflows. Constraining the exact bit ranges isolates datapath testing to "normal" mathematical environments, avoiding false-positive bugs in the verification environment. This code executes purely in simulator memory.
